column20:
Five things I am grateful for in the past 24 hours:

Waking up to a beautiful sunrise and starting the day with a sense of wonder and gratitude.
Having a heartwarming conversation with my parents, feeling their love and support.
Enjoying a delicious home-cooked meal that brought comfort and satisfaction.
Receiving an unexpected compliment from a colleague, brightening my day.
Being able to unwind and relax in the evening with a good book, escaping into another world.
If I were to choose one entry, let's say "Having a heartwarming conversation with my parents, feeling their love and support," life without them would be drastically different. Their presence and unconditional love provide me with a sense of stability, emotional support, and a feeling of belonging. If they were not present in my life, I might feel a profound sense of loss and loneliness. Their guidance and encouragement have been invaluable in shaping my values and beliefs. Without them, I might struggle to navigate through life's challenges and decisions, longing for their wise counsel and comforting presence. Their absence would leave an irreplaceable void in my life, and I would deeply miss the warmth and love that they bring to every interaction.

Thank you for taking a chance on me. I may not have been the most qualified, but you gave me that opportunity and I'd never be as successful as I am today if you hadn't done so. column14: My cat was diagnosed with ear polyps and I was told it would be a lot of money to do the surgery. I will be doing the surgery. So I checked on my savings and it looks like I can manage it, thankfully. The interesting event after that was realizing my vacation plans will be off for the next year as a result, but I feel the choice is worth it, because I love my cat. Unrelated, I discovered that cut-up hot dogs are great in my leftover beans. I mean, it sounds lame, but it was very tasty! I also got a weather report stating that it will finally be under 110 degrees, which is a big deal for summer in the desert. Fifth event, let's see... I was outside, watering my rose bushes, and I could hear the neighbor's goats bleating--he's a farmer. It was otherwise dead quiet, so it was surreal to hear the goats as I worked.

column19:
I am grateful for doing some yard work that I had been putting off. It is getting to where I want it, and it looks nice. I wanted to clean up the years and plant a few things in certain spots. It is still a working progress, but I have accomplished a good deal this week. I gave myself joy by doing so. I could have accomplished more, but I will get to it eventually.

Another thing that I have accomplished this week is doing general cleaning. I had put off doing some cleaning tasks that I typically try to do every week, for a few weeks. I did those tasks that I need to and it makes me feel good to have done that cleaning. The house feels clean now instead of dirty. I gave myself a good feeling by cleaning what I need to. I could have did more cleaning, but I can do some more another time.

I am grateful for placing an online order buying some things I need that I have been putting off. I bought items that I really need but didn't want to spend money on so put off. I finally just bought the things and feel good about it. I am glad I bought those items. I gave myself ease of mind and less stress by doing so. I could have bought a few other things that I need, but I can do that some other time.

Hi Dad,

I'm really grateful for the listening ear you've lended me over the past couple days with you as I've shared my recent ADHD/autism diagnosis. It felt amazing to get your support and love -- and also to swap stories about our own experiences and find a new way for us to relate and understand one another. I feel these disabilities often have a very negative light in our modern world, so it was so nice to feel accepted and have my work in getting help celebrated! I'll always remember how you made me feel. I love you!

column20:
5 things that I'm grateful for:
1. My family
2. My best friend
3. The community and support that I have at my university/graduate program
4. That I live so closely to the mountains and can visit them whenever I want to
5. All of the different kinds of books that I have to choose from

I am choosing to write about 3, or the community that I have in my graduate program at my university. 

I have had a bit of a difficult time in my gradaute program this summer, mainly because I am trying to balance working on my thesis, the house renovations that my family is doing, and trying to financially support my family through my income/setting up my income and jobs for the Fall semester. Recently, this has been hitting me really hard, mainly because I have switched positions and will not be making as much money as I was last academic year. My friend at the school, who is in my year of graduate school, really sat down with me and asked how I was doing, if I was overwhelmed, what I was worried about, etc. She ended up hugging me as I started crying and let me know that she was there for me, that things will work out, etc. I honestly don't know what I would do without her support, as well as the support of my advisors at the university. The fact that, at every twist and turn, I have a net of people who are there to catch me if I start to have problems is such a massive blessing. Knowing that there are people who care, legitimately, and who are willing to help me if I fall into crisis is absolutely vital to me being in graduate school and succeeding right now.
column119: I think it was about understanding how people's outlooks change when they take the time to reflect on things that they are grateful for. I could imagine there might be another treatment where participants write about something negative that happened to them?
column120: Maybe that those who reflect on a positive experience/gratitude tend to have a more positive outlook than those who reflect on a negative experience/do not reflect on any experience?
column122: Yes, I think it did. I wrote down three things that I was grateful for every day when I was a teenager, and I really think that it helped. Now, I do that activity, but I also participate in mindfulness and loving-kindness meditations, which I've found to be even more impactful. In those meditations I also often reflect on gratitude, and it even helps me go even deeper into that by connecting feelings of gratitude with physical sensations, and learning how to really find gratitude for the simplest things in life, like a sunset.
column125: Maybe making that textbox where participants answer whether their gratitude practices worked larger, so that it's easier to see and edit text

To my friend that has helped me through a very tough and trying part of my life. I cannot express how you truly saved my life. That is something I can truly never repay. I have never had anyone that I have truly felt safe with and that is one of the main words I can use to describe the way you make me feel. It is safe and that is something I have never experienced with anyone else.

Thank you for that and for so many things.
